</p><textarea readonly="" accesskey="," id="wpTextbox1" cols="80" rows="25" style="" class="mw-editfont-monospace" lang="en" dir="ltr" name="wpTextbox1"> '''Original Agenda Linked Data for Language Technology (LD4LT)'''
   
  '''21 March, Athens, Greece''' co-located with the [http://2014.data-forum.eu/ European Data Forum 2014].
  '''The Meeting will take place at the Royal Olympic Hotel, Conference Room 1''' 

Linked Data (LD) has proven beneficial in many new and unforeseen ways for Language Technology (LT) and the newly gained interoperability and availability of LT data and services is currently receiving industry adoption. The Workshop will offer several short talks around the topics of Linguistic resources available in the linked data format and their potential impact on research and industry. We will explore together the advantages of promoting free, open  and interoperable language resources as Linked Open Data (LOD) to lower the entry cost to innovating in the use of such resources and technologies in research and industry. We will also aim at exploring how Linguistic Linked Licensed Data open new opportunities for market-based linguistic data exchange.  

In summary, we aim at bringing together stakeholders involved in the linguistic data value chain in order to explore new use cases and  business models for reusing existing and future language (open or licensed) linked data resources and platforms for the joint development and hosting of multi–language data sets and services in different types of applications such as content analytics, machine translation, sentiment analysis, term disambiguation, etc. 

With the foundation of the [http://www.w3.org/community/ld4lt/ '''Linked Data for Language Technologies''' (LD4LT) W3C community group], this event will start the discussion, analyse current trends and offer a crystallization point to coordinate the development of future LD-based LT applications. The [http://www.w3.org/community/ld4lt/wiki/LD4LT_Group_Kick-Off_and_Roadmap_Meeting LD4LT Group Kick-Off Meeting and Roadmap meeting] is supported by the [http://lider-project.eu/ LIDER EU project], the [http://www.multilingualweb.eu/ MultilingualWeb community], the [http://nlp2rdf.org NLP2RDF] project, the [http://linguistics.okfn.org/ Working Group for Open Data in Linguistics] as well as the [http://dbpedia.org DBpedia Project]. 

As input to the discussion and the work of the LD4LT group, we invite you to take a few short minutes to fill in the [https://www.w3.org/2002/09/wbs/1/ld4lt-wbs1/ first LIDER '''survey''']. During the kick-off meeting, via the survey and through the LD4LT group, you will have the opportunity to offer your view on how linked data and language technology should benefit each other.

 
== Registration and Position Statement == 
The LT4LD Kick-Off meeting is a '''free community event''' - there is no admission fee for participants, but registration is required via this [https://www.w3.org/2002/09/wbs/1/lider-rmws-20140321/ online form] (a free W3C Account or only your mail address needed).

At the workshop we want to give you room for a position statement: what are you ideas / technologies / use cases related to Linked Data and Language Technology? If you are interested in making a position statement a the workshop, please indicate this in this in your registration form by providing a short title. We assume about 10 minutes per statement but will decide about detailed timing depending on the number of statements.

== Schedule (9:00 - 17:00 EET) ==


=== Session 1 Challenges (9:00 - 10:40) Chair: Dave Lewis ===
* Welcome and Introduction (LD4LT Group Chair and Dave Lewis) (10 min)
* Introduction of participants (10min)
* A. Gomez-Perez: Challenges of Linked Data 4 Language Technology (20 min)
* Hans Uszkoreit: Language Technologies and Linked Data: Opportunities, Challenges and Synergies (DFKI, Language Technology Lab) (20 min)
* Nicoletta Calzolari: Open Language Resources &amp; Meta-Resources: a Treasure and a Challenge for Linked Data (CNR) (20 min)
* Stelios Piperidis (20 min): Opening and Linking Data and Processing Services

=== Coffee (10:40 - 11:10) ===

=== Session 2 Impulses (11:10 - 13:00)  Chair: Felix Sasaki ===
* Phil Archer: Demanding Multilingual Schemata (W3C) (20 min)
* Felix Sasaki: ITS 2.0 - Foster Multilingual Schema (and data?) creation (10 min)
* Arno Scharl: Semantic Systems for Web Intelligence and Decision Support (20 min)
* Briefing from W3C Community Groups:
** Philipp Cimiano: OntoLex (10 min)
** Jorge Gracia: Best Practices for Multilingual Linked Open Data (BPMLOD) (10min)
** Gabi Vulcu: Linked Data Models for Emotion and Sentiment Analysis (10 min)
* Vakali Athena (5 min)
* Brainstorm about activities and timelines. Goal: create a group charter (25 min)

=== Lunch (13:00 - 14:00) ===

=== Session 3 Position Statements and Industry Perspective (14:00 - 15:20) Chair: Philipp Cimiano ===
Presentations by companies and industrial stakeholders about current problems as well as existing solutions

* Position Statements:
** Benjamin Martin (5 min) 
** Tatiana Gornostay (5 min)
** McCrae John (5 min)
** Nadalis Costas (5 min)
** Giannis Stoitsis (5 min)
** Phil Ritchie (5 min)
** Daniel Vila (5 min)

* Industry Perspectives:
** Ilan Kernermann, K Dictionaries (15min)
** Uroš Milošević (Institute Mihajlo Pupin): Rozeta (15 min)

=== Coffee (15:20 - 15:45) ===

=== Session 4 Requirements and Use Case Discussion (15:35 - 16:40) Chair: Dave Lewis ===

This session has two topics:

# Reference Architecture: In the LIDER project a reference architecture for working with linguistic linked data is being developed. In the session we will gather feedback on requirements for this architecture.
# Use Cases: An online survey on areas of industrial interest and use case areas for linked data in language technology is currently underway. In the session we will gather use cases from the participants.

To complement the use case discussion, the results of the survey will be summarized, together with input from the keynote speakers, existing community groups, and industrial position statement, to seed an open mike discussion on the priorities and concerns of industry in considering the use of linked data for language technologies.  (45 min)

=== Wrap Up (16:40 - 17:00) ===

